{"type":"message","id":"8eeefb95","parentId":"55953fc2","timestamp":"2026-03-22T22:05:38.549Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me also fix the `_query_impact` method. Currently it returns local variable accesses which aren't useful. The issue is that when we call `_query_impact(\"EventBasedStore._apply_focus_decay\")`, it finds `self.facts.values` because that's a reference inside the method. But what the user actually wants to know is \"what functions call this method?\" or \"what code depends on this?\".\n\nThe `_query_impact` method traverses the graph from the target node and finds everything downstream. But `self.facts.values` is a local attribute access, not a function call from outside. This is a fundamental limitation of static analysis — without inter-procedural analysis, we can't tell which external code paths call this method.\n \nThe real problem is that our graph only has intraprocedural edges right now, so `_query_impact` only finds what happens inside the method itself. I need to check if inter-procedural edges actually exist in the graph — if they don't, then I should fall back to `_query_dependents` instead, which would at least show what functions reference this method from outside.","thinkingSignature":"3d7ff6be7db8e3d967877049f19e61dcc1370b2e42ad410991381b41b89bd297"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2m5skh3ajgyn_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python C:/Users/Zwmar/.openclaw/workspace/debug_query5.py 2>&1","timeout":60}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":36032,"output":287,"cacheRead":12619,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48938,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774217130481}}
